Q: Why does the potential decrease across a resistor when current flows through it?
-When current flows through a resistor the electrons collide with atoms in the resistor‚Äôs lattice. These collisions convert electrical energy into heat energy. The voltage drop across the resistor represents the energy lost per unit charge as it passes.Now the electric potential decreases because the energy carried by the charges is partially spent to heat the resistor.
