When an electron jumps from n=2 ‚Üí n=4, it absorbs energy.  
Now, if it ‚Äúcoincidentally‚Äù receives **exact energy** equal to the gap between n=4 ‚Üí n=6,  
then YES ‚Äî it can jump again to n=6.  

But if that exact energy isn‚Äôt available (like from a photon of that specific frequency),  
it **won‚Äôt re-jump** on its own.  

It also **won‚Äôt fall back** immediately unless it loses energy (by emitting a photon).  
So, it stays in n=4 temporarily ‚Äî excited but stable till something interacts again.